{meta: title Cocaine Blues}
{meta: artist Johnny Cash}
{meta: writer T.J. Arnall}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[C]Early one morning while making the rounds
[G7]I took a shot of cocaine and I shot my woman down
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
I went right home and I went to bed
[C]I stuck that loving 44 beneath my head
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
Got up next morning and I grabbed that gun
[G7]Took a shot of cocaine and away I run
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
Made a good run but I run too slow
[C]They overtook me down in Juarez Mexico
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
Late in the hot joints taking the pills
[G7]In walked the sheriff from Jericho Hill
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
He said Willy Lee your name is not Jack Brown
[C]You're the dirty hack that shot your woman down
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 7}
Said yes oh yes my name is Willy Lee
[G7]If you've got the warrant just a-read it to me
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 8}
Shot her down because she made me slow
[C]I thought I was her daddy but she had five more
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 9}
When I was arrested I was dressed in black
[G7]They put me on a train and they took me back
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 10}
Had no friend for to go my bail
[C]They slapped my dried up carcass in that country jail
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 11}
Early next morning bout a half past nine
[G7]I spied the sheriff coming down the line
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 12}
Talked and he coughed as he cleared his throat
[C]He said come on you dirty heck into that district court
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 13}
Into the courtroom my trial began
[G7]Where I was handled by twelve honest men
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 14}
Just before the jury started out
[C]I saw the little judge commence to look about
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 15}
In about five minutes in walked the man
[G7]Holding the verdict in his right hand
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 16}
The verdict read in the first degree
[C]I hollered Lordy Lordy have a mercy on me
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 17}
The judge he smiled as he picked up his pen
[G7]99 years in the Folsom pen
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 18}
99 years underneath that ground
[C]I can't forget the day I shot that bad bitch down
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 19}
[F]Come on you've gotta listen unto me
[G7]Lay off that whiskey and let that cocaine [C]be
{end_of_verse}
